data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new implicit span conversions. In your expression tree, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**. Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>` parameters, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` (or use `.AsEnumerable()`) to force the old `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`Reverse()`** on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension returning `void`). Use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` in those cases.
